As Urban explains it, =E2=80=9CYou have to remember something about what it=
=E2=80=99s like to stand on a time graph: you can=E2=80=99t see what=E2=80=
=99s to your right.=E2=80=9D It=E2=80=99s possible to look backwards with r=
elative certainty; it=E2=80=99s impossible to look forward with any certain=
ty, particularly when progress itself is increasing at an increasing pace.=
=C2=A0
To illustrate the point, Urban wrote up a thought experiment:=C2=A0
Imagine that you got in a time machine back to 1750, grabbed someone alive =
then, and then brought them back to the present to show him around and watc=
h his reactions. Everything we take for granted -- cars, tall buildings, iP=
hones, live sports broadcasts, recorded music, Google Maps -- would blow hi=
s mind in such a major way that he wouldn=E2=80=99t just be shocked, he mig=
ht actually die.=C2=A0
If that guy wanted to pay it forward and kill someone with shock by bringin=
g them to 1750, he couldn=E2=80=99t just go back ~250 years and grab someon=
e from 1500. 1750 and 1500 are too similar. There would be some new things,=
 but nothing that would kill the 1500s guy. To get the same effect, Urban g=
uesses that he would have to pick someone up who lived around ~12,000 BC, b=
efore the First Agricultural Revolution. That guy, in turn, couldn=E2=80=99=
t just go back 12,000 years to 24,000 BC, =E2=80=9Che=E2=80=99d have to go =
back over 100,000 years and get someone he could show fire and language to =
for the first time.=E2=80=9D
He called the amount of time you=E2=80=99d have to go ahead to be shocked e=
nough at the world to die a Die Progress Unit (DPU). The DPU is a colorful =
illustration of an idea from futurist Ray Kurzweil, the author of The Singu=
larity is Near: the Law of Accelerating Returns.=C2=A0
The Law of Accelerating Returns states that the rate of change of progress =
accelerates because humans can use the technology at their disposal to prog=
ress faster than previous generations could without the technology.=C2=A0
This is demonstrably true, using DPUs or actual numbers, but according to U=
rban, there are three reasons we can=E2=80=99t grok the impact of exponenti=
al progress:=C2=A0
When it comes to history, we think in straight lines. It=E2=80=99s really h=
ard to grasp how much crazier the future is going to get, because most peop=
le extrapolate based on the past growth rate, and even the more optimistic =
and adventurous ones will extrapolate from the present growth rate.=C2=A0
Source: WaitButWhy
If you accept that the rate of progress is accelerating, then it follows th=
at using past or even present rates undershoots.=C2=A0
The trajectory of very recent history often tells a distorted story. Making=
 this even harder, in the short-term, assuming an accelerating growth rate =
might make you look silly or lose money. The progression isn=E2=80=99t smoo=
th. A period of rapid growth might give way to a period of slower growth. P=
rogress happens in S-Curves -- similar to the Gartner Hype Cycle that we so=
 often talk about here -- and it might even look like we=E2=80=99re regress=
ing in certain areas at points. But over time, if you zoom out, those are j=
ust squiggles on an exponential curve arcing up and to the right.
Source: WaitButWhy
Our own experience makes us stubborn old men about the future. We have live=
d through past growth rates. We=E2=80=99ve never lived through future growt=
h. Therefore, it=E2=80=99s a lot easier for us to intuit what the future wi=
ll be like by extrapolating linearly based on what we=E2=80=99ve actually e=
xperienced. Yes, things will be different, we all know that, but they=E2=80=
=99ll be different in predictable ways. We expect that anything that deviat=
es too far from our past experience, or historical averages, will revert to=
 the mean.=C2=A0
So we=E2=80=99re making progress, and progress keeps getting faster, but ho=
w does that happen?=C2=A0
Two years later, in a 2017 post called Neuralink and the Brain=E2=80=99s Ma=
gical Future [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkMGKxCAQRL9mPAY1GvXgYS_7=
G0FjZyJjNJh2h_z9OjMLC00VdFMU_RaHcC_1skc5kbxkxusAm-F5JkCEStoJdY7BsonrUQpDghW=
BaalJPOe1AuwuJou1ATmaT3FxGEt-JyjlkmyWmVWzicpJLXpVqwlMMCroCJT7xQT56XUtRMgLWP=
iBepUMJNkN8Thv49eNf_d5uoi-4XO7hqXsfcEpU92o6JKhVZdifgwb7olEyylnVHfhUgk5sIGuy=
gvHRQgMqHGr08EJH7gapdNqZTdB9zsfzuZPdMvj1UGqzQV9qTHf-_mxuR3S-9BfnbvvLUe8ZsjO=
JwgfCviB-eYy3yFD7ZDD7PCFUBlqqJok-_u6YxqNYFyIkfTmUHoq_5f-Aorvih0], Urban int=
roduced another useful analogy: the Human Colossus. We evolved from blobs o=
f cells that did nothing to humans who learned to communicate with language=
 to people who could mass produce books and share them across the world, at=
 which point humanity became the Human Colossus, essentially one large orga=
nism with shared knowledge. Computers and then the internet turbocharged th=
at knowledge (and tool) sharing to the point that, today, you can go online=
, connect with anyone, download practically any information, and even fork =
full codebases or download designs for physical things.=C2=A0
Source: WaitButWhy
By connecting to the internet, any individual human can access all human kn=
owledge. Things that took thousands of people millennia, centuries, or year=
s to develop can be used and remixed by one person in one second. We have m=
ore building blocks than ever before, and we can use those building blocks =
to make new building blocks more quickly.=C2=A0
The takeaway is that human knowledge compounds, we build new things on the =
shoulders of giants at a faster and faster pace, and our brains are not goo=
d at understanding all of that in the moment.=C2=A0
If you pause, though, you can feel it happening all around us, right now.=
